In my app I have a deep hierarchy if containers. I have performance problems. So I'm looking for a way to decrease render calls and matrix transformations.

I'm trying to use flatten: cpu usage decreases by 20%, but number of draw-calles increases from 39 to 214. I have tried to change the following method of Sprite:

``` as3
public override function render(support:RenderSupport, parentAlpha:Number):void  {
            // some code
            if (mFlattenedContents || mFlattenRequested)
            {
                if (mFlattenedContents == null)
                    mFlattenedContents = new <QuadBatch>[];                
                if (mFlattenRequested)
                {
                    QuadBatch.compile(this, mFlattenedContents);
                    support.applyClipRect(); // compiling filters might change scissor rect. :-\
                    mFlattenRequested = false;
                }                
                var alpha:Number = parentAlpha * this.alpha;
                var numBatches:int = mFlattenedContents.length;
                var mvpMatrix:Matrix = support.mvpMatrix;
// following 2 lines are removed, not finish prev batch                
                // support.finishQuadBatch();
                // support.raiseDrawCount(numBatches);                
                for (var i:int=0; i<numBatches; ++i)
                {
                    var quadBatch:QuadBatch = mFlattenedContents[i];
                    var blendMode:String = quadBatch.blendMode == BlendMode.AUTO ?
                        support.blendMode : quadBatch.blendMode;
// remove render-custom
                        // quadBatch.renderCustom(mvpMatrix, alpha, blendMode);
// add this line instead
            support.batchQuadBatch(quadBatch, parentAlpha);
                }
            }
            // some code
        }
```

This code keeps decreasing the CPU usage and keeps draw-calls low.
I know that "batchQuadBatch" is not the best option. So I am thinking on a way to replace quadBatch vector with quad vector, that could be quicker.

PS 
The best thing I can dream off is to stop rendering some display-object completely: no render, not upload-vector buffer, no calculating triangles, but keep them on the screen frozen. The weakest point of starling is that it has no dirty-checks (to my mind), so it would be great to have "freeze" option.

How about adding a simple method to `DisplayObject` for searching an ancestor of a given class? Something like this:

``` as3
        public function findAncestor(clazz:Class):DisplayObject
        {
            var currentObject:DisplayObject = mParent;

            while(currentObject != null)
            {
                if(currentObject is clazz)
                    return currentObject;

                currentObject = currentObject.mParent;
            }

            return null;
        }
```

